  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Brisbane sellers regularly worry that running a campaign across school holidays will damage the result. The intuition is reasonable: families travel, attention drops, open home attendance from family buyers can fall sharply. But the practical reality is more nuanced. School holidays reshape buyer activity rather than stopping it, and a seller who calibrates the campaign to the suburb, the property type, and the most likely buyer pool can use the period strategically rather than just enduring it.</p>

      <p>This article walks through Queensland's four school holiday windows, what changes on the buyer side and the seller side during those windows, the campaign timing decisions that matter most, and what to actually do during the period to maintain campaign momentum.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The four Queensland school holiday windows each year</h2>
      <p>Queensland operates on a four-term school year with four holiday breaks. The term 1 break falls in early April and is structured around Easter, typically two weeks in length. The term 2 break runs from late June into mid-July, two to three weeks. The term 3 break sits in mid-September to early October, also around two weeks, with a long weekend often embedded. The summer break is the longest, mid-December to late January, six weeks or more, and is the most disruptive to normal market activity. Each window has a different effect on buyer behaviour.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The 2028 specifics for autumn campaigns</h2>
      <p>The term 1 break in 2028 runs from Mar 31 to Apr 16, with the Easter long weekend embedded across Apr 14-17. This creates a 2.5-week window of disrupted normal buyer behaviour, sitting awkwardly across the back end of March and the first half of April. Sellers running campaigns through this period need to make explicit decisions about open home strategy, marketing intensity, and the launch and close timing of the campaign. Drifting into the holiday window without a plan is the most common cause of underperformance through autumn campaigns.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens during school holidays: buyer side</h2>
      <p>Families with school-age children are travelling or focused on holiday activities. Attendance at open homes from this segment drops by 40 to 60% in the peak holiday week, depending on the suburb and the holiday calendar. The drop is largest in the middle week of a two-week break, when most families have either travelled or are doing local activities. The drop is smaller in the bookend weekends.</p>

      <p>At the same time, families who are using the break to do concentrated property research can be highly engaged buyers. They are not casually looking; they have used the time off work to systematically work through suburbs, school zones, and shortlisted properties. This segment is smaller in number but stronger in conversion than typical weekend traffic.</p>

      <p>Investor and DINK (dual income, no kids) buyer activity is largely unaffected by school holidays. These segments do not have the same calendar pressures and continue to inspect, research, and offer through the holiday period at near-normal rates. For property types that primarily attract these buyers (one and two bedroom units, low-maintenance townhouses, investment-grade properties), school holidays barely register.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens during school holidays: seller side</h2>
      <p>Many sellers reduce their campaign intensity during school holidays, often by reducing open home frequency, pausing marketing, or simply being less responsive to buyer inquiry. This can be a strategic mistake in some property types and a sensible adjustment in others, and the difference is the buyer pool.</p>

      <p>For family-targeted properties (three to five bedroom houses in catchment zones, larger family-oriented Queenslanders, properties with strong school appeal), school holidays are typically below-average for activity. It is reasonable to schedule lighter open homes (or private inspections only) during the holiday peak, and resume full intensity in the first weekend after the break.</p>

      <p>For non-family properties (units, apartments, townhouses, investments), school holidays are nearly normal weeks. The campaign should proceed largely as planned with no material reduction in marketing or inspection schedule.</p>

      <p>For catchment-zone properties (homes in a desirable Brisbane state school catchment, where the school zone is a primary buyer driver), school holidays are an interesting opportunity. Families using the break to research school zone options before term 2 starts are a captive audience. Active engagement during the holidays can capture committed buyers who are making the school zone decision in real time.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Campaign timing decisions</h2>
      <p>If you are planning to launch a family-targeted property, avoid the very first weekend of school holidays. The first weekend is when family activity drops most sharply (travel begins, school holiday programs start) and the launch loses its first-impression advantage.</p>

      <p>Launching the week before holidays maximises pre-holiday inquiry, with families doing pre-trip research and shortlisting, ready to inspect on the bookend weekends or just after the break. Alternatively, launching the first week after holidays catches the rebound, with refreshed buyers and lower competing listings. Both work; what does not work is launching mid-holiday into a thin audience.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Open home strategy during school holidays</h2>
      <p>During the holiday peak, schedule fewer but better-targeted open homes. A single one-hour open home with a qualified buyer expectation is more useful than three sparsely-attended open homes. Consider inspection-by-appointment for serious buyers, which allows you to focus the campaign on high-intent inquiries rather than casual foot traffic.</p>

      <p>Use the time productively. Refresh the marketing if it has been live for a few weeks: new photos in different light, refreshed copy, refreshed staging. The holidays are a natural moment to reset the campaign without it feeling like a price reduction or a strategy change to the buyer pool.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Communication during school holidays</h2>
      <p>Maintain regular contact with all interested buyers through the holiday period. The campaign should not appear paused, even if open home volume reduces. Buyers who feel the campaign has gone quiet often move on to other listings, and a re-engaged buyer in week six is usually a weaker negotiator than the same buyer engaged continuously from week three.</p>

      <p>Use the holiday period for substantive communication: agent feedback summaries, comparable sales updates in the suburb, follow-up calls with engaged buyers. Buyers who feel actively managed are more likely to commit when the post-holiday inspection happens.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The post-holiday rebound</h2>
      <p>The first one to two weekends after a school holiday break typically see a strong rebound in buyer activity. Buyers come back refreshed, decisive, and often with a clearer view on what they want after a break from active searching. Competing listings are often paused or running on tired campaigns from before the break, which means your property gets disproportionate attention.</p>

      <p>Plan the campaign to be in strong shape for the post-holiday weekends, with refreshed marketing, a clear pricing position, and a confident open home presentation. The post-holiday weekends are often the strongest of the campaign for properties that managed the holiday window well.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What NOT to do</h2>
      <p>Do not pause the listing entirely during school holidays. Buyers searching during holidays will not see paused properties, and the listing loses online presence at a moment when post-holiday buyers are starting to research for the rebound. The cost of staying live is small; the cost of going dark is larger than most sellers assume.</p>

      <p>Do not assume school holidays affect all buyer types equally. Calibrate to your specific buyer pool. A two-bedroom Bulimba townhouse and a four-bedroom Camp Hill family home will have completely different holiday-period buyer dynamics, and the campaign decisions should reflect that.</p>

      <p>Do not start price reductions during the holidays. The data on inquiry and inspection volume during the holiday period is too thin to support a meaningful pricing decision. Worse, a price reduction during a known low-activity window signals weakness to the buyer pool, who then assume the reduction was forced rather than strategic. Wait for the post-holiday rebound to assess where pricing actually sits relative to buyer demand.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>
      <p>School holidays are not market shutdowns. They are reshapings of buyer activity that calibrate by property type and buyer pool. Identify which buyer segment your property primarily attracts, then plan the campaign rhythm around that segment's holiday behaviour. Use the period strategically: pre-launch preparation, photo refreshes, agent strategy reviews, and engagement with buyers who are using the break to research seriously. Emerge ready for the post-holiday surge with a campaign that has stayed live, stayed visible, and stayed in good shape through the window. Sellers who plan for the holidays consistently outperform sellers who try to ignore them or who pause without a plan.</p>

